[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "text": "Let's see gradient clipping in action. We have two scenarios: unclipped gradients on the left, and clipped gradients on the right. Both start at the same position on this loss landscape.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "text": "First, we compute the gradient at this point. The gradient value is negative 2.4, which is quite large.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 3,
    "text": "Now we apply gradient clipping with a threshold of 1.0. The unclipped gradient remains at negative 2.4, but the clipped version is bounded to negative 1.0.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "text": "Watch what happens when we take the update step. The unclipped gradient causes a massive jump across the loss landscape, essentially exploding to the other side.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "text": "In contrast, the clipped gradient produces a small, controlled step that moves smoothly toward the minimum.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "text": "Without gradient clipping, large gradients cause training instability and exploding parameters. With clipping, we ensure bounded updates for stable convergence.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  }
]
